The certainty that the glitches were systemic, widespread, and worsening pushed Leo back into the Sim's hidden networks. He needed to know what others were seeing, thinking. He navigated the encrypted backchannels to the virtual speakeasy forum he'd found.\
The atmosphere there was more agitated than before. More users shared experiences, no longer just philosophical musings, but concrete examples: whole city blocks experiencing temporary 'texture flickering', conjured vehicles momentarily losing physics coherence, complex simulations generating impossible paradoxes. The term 'reality bleed' was gaining traction.\
Leo lurked, reading threads, absorbing the growing unease. He saw debates raging \'96 some users demanding answers from 'System Admin' (a concept most dismissed as myth), others advocating for digital 'safe zones' or attempting complex rituals to 'ward off' the anomalies. One group, calling themselves the 'Pattern Weavers', claimed the glitches weren't random but formed a complex, evolving pattern, a language they were trying to decipher.\
He risked another anonymous message, more specific this time: 
\f2\i 'Detected structured data signals embedded within Type 7 instability events. Non-standard encoding. Possible external origin?'
\f0\i0 \
The response came quickly, from a user named 'Oracle': 
